Basic Calculations

Below is an example of confidence interval by hand. The availability of copy-and-past, as well as the quick access to history commands (arrow up/down), makes it efficient to do basic calculations in R.

0.56 + 1.96 * sqrt(0.56 * (1 - 0.56) / 200)
0.56 - 1.96 * sqrt(0.56 * (1 - 0.56) / 200)

The idea of assigning variables can be appealing to students, too.

p = 0.56
n = 200
p + 1.96 * sqrt(p * (1 - p) / n)
p - 1.96 * sqrt(p * (1 - p) / n)

Summary statistics

x = c(1.2, 2.4, 3.0, 4.2, 5.9, 6.1, 7.2)
mean(x)
sd(x)
quantile(x, 0.3, type = 2)

Distributions

R has built-in probability density function (pdf), cumulative distribution function (cdf), and quantile functions for popular distributions.

  • Binomial distribution (e.g., n=30 and p=0.8).

    dbinom(17, 30, 0.8)
pbinom(17, 30, 0.8)

  • Normal distribution (e.g., =0 and =1).

    pnorm(-2, 0, 1)
qnorm(0.975, 0, 1)

  • Student t-distribution (e.g., df=29).

    pt(1.72, 29)
qt(0.975, 29)

Inference

  • Categorical variable, e.g., p=88/100 against p0=0.82.

    binom.test(88, 100, conf.level = 0.95)                   # Confidence interval
binom.test(88, 100, p = 0.82, alternative = "two.sided") # Hypotheses test
binom.test(88, 100, p = 0.82, alternative = "less")      # Hypotheses test
binom.test(88, 100, p = 0.82, alternative = "greater")   # Hypotheses test

  • Numeric variable with a given raw data x against =2.5.

    t.test(x, conf.level = 0.95)                   # Confidence intervals
t.test(x, mu = 2.5, alternative = "two.sided") # Hypotheses test
t.test(x, mu = 2.5, alternative = "greater")   # Hypotheses test
t.test(x, mu = 2.5, alternative = "less")      # Hypotheses test

Bargraphs, boxplots, and histograms can be easily generated by R. They are good for

  • Lecture illustrations.
  • Student project.
    • Project example: Use R to reproduce a graph that you found in a (news) article that looks interesting to you.

Shiny is an R package that builds interactive web apps using R codes. When deployed on a server, the interactive features allows the apps to facilitate:

  • Simulations
    • Example: Ace a quiz by guessing.
    • Example: Create the sampling distribution.
  • Quick class survey.
    • Example: Understand the standard deviation.
  • Data randomization in exams.
    • Example.
